tic culture, led to diverse forms of religious devotion and institutions.Contributors: Maria Pia Alberzoni on heresy; Frances Andrews on urban religion; Cécile Caby on monasticism; Giovanna Casagrande on mendicants; George Dameron on Florence; Antonella degl'Innocenti on saints; Marina Gazzini on lay confraternities; Maureen C. Miller on bishops; Agostino Paravicini Bagliani and Pietro Silanos on the papacy and Italian politics; Antonio Rigon on clerical confraternities; Neslihan Şenocak on the pievi and care of souls; Giovanni Vitolo on Naples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristian lifezItalyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChristianityxSocial aspectszItalyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aChurch historyyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aReligious Studies. 4aWEST EUROPEAN HISTORY. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  areligion in medieval Italy, medieval monasticism, medieval confraternities, mendicant orders, medieval religious history, history of religion in Italy, Catholic church in Italy.1 aAlberzoni, Maria Pia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrews, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaby, Cécile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasagrande, Giovanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDameron, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegl’Innocenti, Antonella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGazzini, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Maureen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParavicini Bagliani, Agostino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParavicini Bagliani, Agostino, eeditor.4edt4http://i